               <head>Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī by Ḥusayn Vāʻiz̤ Kāshifī</head>
               <msContents
                  class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh94005331 https://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh91005357 https://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008104964">
                  <summary>A Persian didactic treatise on morality for princes called
                        <title>Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī</title> written by Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn Vāʻiẓ Kāshifī
                     and dedicated to the last Timurid ruler, <persName>Sultān Ḥusayn
                        Bāyqarā</persName> (1438-1506; r. 1469-1506), and his son, <persName>Muḥsin
                        Mīrzā</persName>. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_903A-item1">
                     <author key="Viaf_167206013">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Kamāl al-Dīn Ḥusayn ibn ʿAlī Vāʿiẓ
                           Kāshifī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">کمال الدّین حسین بن علی واعظ کاشفی </persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_219">Akhlāq-i Muḥsinī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">اخلاق محسنی</title>
                     <colophon>(f. 186v) Transcription completed on 24 Sha'ban 1137 (8 May 1725).
                        Copied by <persName role="scr">Abū al-Fatḥ Multānī</persName>. </colophon>
                     <note>
                        <p>Title is recorded as <title>Akhlāq al-Muḥsinī</title> in note on on f.1r.
                        </p>
                     </note>
                     <note>
                        <p>The patron's name has been erased from the colophon. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. i+186. <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>226</height>
                              <width>142</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>161</height>
                              <width>70</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>India Office Library stamped foliation with every fifth leaf numbered
                              in pencil. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Good condition. The folios have been trimmed for binding. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="15">
                           <p>15 lines per page, with verses arranged in two columns.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʻlīq; Arabic quotations in naskh; copied in black ink, with headings
                           and overlinings in red. Copyist is <persName role="scr" key="">Abū
                              al-Fatḥ Multānī</persName>. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="headpiece">Illuminated polychrome headpiece dominated by gold
                        and then blue but also containing red, green and brown(<locus>f.
                        1v</locus>). </decoNote>
                     <decoNote>Ruled margins in red, black, gold and blue, with blue single outer
                        frame. </decoNote>
                     <decoNote>All couplets in ruled boxes. </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>A label glued to the binding describes the script as <hi rend="italic"
                           >vilāyatī</hi>. </p>
                     <p>A piece of paper stuck to f. 64r names five books which solidify one's
                        faith. The first of five is the current work. </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1857">
                        <decoNote>Binding wrapped in dark blue cloth. </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Black Government of India Delhi MSS oval stamp (ff. 1r, 2r, 186v). </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin calendar="Hijri-qamari" when="1725-05-08">24 Sha'ban 1237 AH (8
